# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: separation-logic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] In computing, **aliasing** describes a situation in which a data location in memory can be accessed through different symbolic names in the program.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Thus, modifying the data through one name implicitly modifies the values associated with all aliased names, which may not be expected by the programmer.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] As a result, aliasing makes it particularly difficult to understand, analyze and optimize programs.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Aliasing analysers intend to make and compute useful information for understanding aliasing in programs.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Aliasing can occur in any language that can refer to one location in memory with more than one name (for example, with pointers).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] This is a common problem with functions that accept pointer arguments, and their tolerance (or the lack thereof) for aliasing must be carefully documented, particularly for functions that perform complex manipulations on memory areas passed to them.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Controlled aliasing behaviour may be desirable in some cases (that is, aliasing behaviour that is specified, unlike that enabled by memory layout in C).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] The Perl programming language specifies, in some constructs, aliasing behaviour, such as in `foreach` loops.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] This allows certain data structures to be modified directly with less code.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] If one wanted to bypass aliasing effects, one could copy the contents of the index variable into another and change the copy.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Optimizers often have to make conservative assumptions about variables when aliasing is possible.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] For example, knowing the value of a variable (such as `x` is 5) normally allows certain optimizations (such as constant propagation).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] However, the compiler cannot use this information after an assignment to another variable (for example, in C, `*y = 10`) because it could be that `*y` is an alias of `x`.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] This could be the case after an assignment like `y = &x`.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] As an effect of this assignment to `*y`, the value of `x` would be changed as well, so propagating the information that `x` is 5 to the statements following `*y = 10` would be potentially wrong (if `*y` is indeed an alias of `x`).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] However, if there is information about pointers, the constant propagation process could make a query like: can `x` be an alias of `*y`?
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Then, if the answer is no, `x = 5` can be propagated safely.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Another optimization impacted by aliasing is code reordering.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] If the compiler decides that `x` is not aliased by `*y`, then code that uses or changes the value of `x` can be moved before the assignment `*y = 10`, if this would improve scheduling or enable more loop optimizations to be carried out.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] To enable such optimizations in a predictable manner, the ISO standard for the C programming language (including its newer C99 edition, see section 6.5, paragraph 7) specifies that it is illegal (with some exceptions) to access the same memory location using pointers of different types.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] A compiler may therefore assume that such pointers do not alias.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] This rule, known as the **strict aliasing rule**, sometimes allows for impressive increases in performance, but has been known to break some otherwise valid code.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Several software projects intentionally violate this portion of the C99 standard.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] For example, Python 2.x did so to implement reference counting, and required changes to the basic object structs in Python 3 to enable this optimization.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] The Linux kernel does this because strict aliasing causes problems with optimization of inlined code.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] In such cases, when compiled with gcc, the option `-fno-strict-aliasing` is invoked to prevent unwanted optimizations that could yield unexpected code.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] The term *aliasing* is also used to describe the situation where, due to either a hardware design choice or a hardware failure, one or more of the available address bits is not used in the memory selection process.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] This may be a design decision if there are more address bits available than are necessary to support the installed memory device(s).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] In a failure, one or more address bits may be shorted together, or may be forced to ground (logic 0) or the supply voltage (logic 1).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] For this example, assuming a memory design with 8 locations, requiring only 3 address lines (or bits, since 23 = 8).
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] In the table above, each of the 8 unique combinations of address bits selects a different memory location.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] In this case, with A2 always being zero, the first four memory locations are duplicated and appear again as the second four.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] Memory locations 4 through 7 have become inaccessible.
[src:separation-logic/aliasing-computing] If this change occurred to a different address bit, the decoding results would be different, but in general the effect would be the same: the loss of a single address bit cuts the available memory space in half, with resulting duplication (aliasing) of the remaining space.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] $A*B$ and $B{-\!\!*}C$ are forms of conjunction and implication that take resources into account (explained below).
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] In addition to these connectives bunched logic has a formula, sometimes written I or emp, which is the unit of *.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] In the original version of bunched logic $\wedge$ and $\Rightarrow$ were the connectives from intuitionistic logic, while a boolean variant takes $\wedge$ and $\Rightarrow$ (and $\neg$ ) as from traditional boolean logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Thus, bunched logic is compatible with constructive principles, but is in no way dependent on them.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The easiest way to understand these formulae is in terms of its truth-functional semantics.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The foundation for this reading of formulae was provided by a forcing semantics $r\models A$ advanced by Pym, where the forcing relation means '*A* holds of resource *r*'.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The semantics is analogous to Kripke's semantics of intuitionistic or modal logic, but where the elements of the model are regarded as resources that can be composed and decomposed, rather than as possible worlds that are accessible from one another.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] where $r_{A}\bullet r_{B}$ is a way of combining resources and $\leq$ is a relation of approximation.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] This semantics of bunched logic draws on prior work in relevance logic (especially the operational semantics of Routley–Meyer), but differs from it by not requiring $r\bullet r\leq r$ and by accepting the semantics of standard intuitionistic or classical versions of $\wedge$ and $\Rightarrow$ .
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The property $r\bullet r\leq r$ is justified when thinking about relevance but denied by considerations of resource; having two copies of a resource is not the same as having one, and in some models (e.g. heap models) $r\bullet r$ might not even be defined.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The standard semantics of $\Rightarrow$ (or of negation) is often rejected by relevantists in their bid to escape the `paradoxes of material implication', which are not a problem from the perspective of modelling resources and so not rejected by bunched logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The semantics is also related to the 'phase semantics' of linear logic, but again is differentiated by accepting the standard (even boolean) semantics of $\wedge$ and $\Rightarrow$ , which in linear logic is rejected in a bid to be constructive.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] These considerations are discussed in detail in an article on resource semantics by Pym, O'Hearn and Yang.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The double version of the deduction theorem of bunched logic has a corresponding category-theoretic structure.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] a categorical model of bunched logic is a single category possessing two closed structures, one symmetric monoidal closed the other cartesian closed.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] A host of categorial models can be given using Day's tensor product construction.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Additionally, the implicational fragment of bunched logic has been given a game semantics.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The algebraic semantics of bunched logic is a special case of its categorical semantics, but is simple to state and can be more approachable.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The boolean version of bunched logic has models as follows.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] and that carries an additional residuated commutative monoid structure.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The proof calculus of bunched logic differs from usual sequent calculi in having a tree-like context of hypotheses instead of a flat list-like structure.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] In its sequent-based proof theories, the context $\Delta$ in an entailment judgement $\Delta \vdash A$ is a finite rooted tree whose leaves are propositions and whose internal nodes are labelled with modes of composition corresponding to the two conjunctions.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The two combining operators, comma and semicolon, are used (for instance) in the introduction rules for the two implications.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The difference between the two composition rules comes from additional rules that apply to them.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The structural rules and other operations on bunches are often applied deep within a tree-context, and not only at the top level: it is thus in a sense a calculus of deep inference.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Corresponding to bunched logic is a type theory having two kinds of function type.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Following the Curry–Howard correspondence, introduction rules for implications correspond to introduction rules for function types.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Here, there are two distinct binders, $\lambda$ and $\alpha$ , one for each kind of function type.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The proof theory of bunched logic has an historical debt to the use of bunches in relevance logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] But the bunched structure can in a sense be derived from the categorical and algebraic semantics: to formulate an introduction rule for ${-\!\!*}$ we should mimick * on the left in sequents, and to introduce $\Rightarrow$ we should mimick $\wedge$ .
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] This consideration leads to the use of two combining operators.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] James Brotherston has done further significant work on a unified proof theory for bunched logic and variants, employing Belnap's notion of display logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Galmiche, Méry, and Pym have provided a comprehensive treatment of bunched logic, including completeness and other meta-theory, based on labelled tableaux.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] In perhaps the first use of substructural type theory to control resources, John C.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Reynolds showed how to use an affine type theory to control aliasing and other forms of interference in ALGOL-like programming languages.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] O'Hearn used bunched type theory to extend Reynolds' system by allowing interference and non-interference to be more flexibly mixed.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] This resolved open problems concerning recursion and jumps in Reynolds' system.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Separation logic is an extension of Hoare logic that facilitates reasoning about mutable data structures that use pointers.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Following Hoare logic the formulae of separation logic are of the form $\{Pre\}program\{Post\}$ , but the preconditions and postconditions are formulae interpreted in a model of bunched logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] It is the undefinedness of the composition on overlapping heaps that models the separation idea.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] This is a model of the boolean variant of bunched logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] that divides the storage accessed by parallel threads.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Later, the greater generality of the resource semantics was utilized: an abstract version of separation logic works for Hoare triples where the preconditions and postconditions are formulae interpreted over an arbitrary partial commutative monoid instead of a particular heap model.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] By suitable choice of commutative monoid, it was surprisingly found that the proofs rules of abstract versions of concurrent separation logic could be used to reason about interfering concurrent processes, for example by encoding rely-guarantee and trace-based reasoning.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Separation logic is the basis of a number of tools for automatic and semi-automatic reasoning about programs, and is used in the Infer program analyzer currently deployed at Facebook.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Bunched logic has been used in connection with the (synchronous) resource-process calculus SCRP in order to give a (modal) logic that characterizes, in the sense of Hennessy–Milner, the compositional structure of concurrent systems.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] SCRP is notable for interpreting $A*B$ in terms of *both* parallel composition of systems and composition of their associated resources.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] The system SCRP is based directly on bunched logic's resource semantics; that is, on ordered monoids of resource elements.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] While direct and intuitively appealing, this choice leads to a specific technical problem: the Hennessy–Milner completeness theorem holds only for fragments of the modal logic that exclude the multiplicative implication and multiplicative modalities.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] This problem is solved by basing resource-process calculus on a resource semantics in which resource elements are combined using two combinators, one corresponding to concurrent composition and one corresponding to choice.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Cardelli, Caires, Gordon and others have investigated a series of logics of process calculi, where a conjunction is interpreted in terms of parallel composition.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Unlike the work of Pym et al. in SCRP, they do not distinguish between parallel composition of systems and composition of resources accessed by the systems.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Their logics are based on instances of the resource semantics that give rise to models of the boolean variant of bunched logic.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Although these logics give rise to instances of boolean bunched logic, they appear to have been arrived at independently, and in any case have significant additional structure in the way of modalities and binders.
[src:separation-logic/bunched-logic] Related logics have been proposed as well for modelling XML data.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] In computer science, **separation logic** is an extension of Hoare logic, a way of reasoning about programs.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Reynolds, Peter O'Hearn, Samin Ishtiaq and Hongseok Yang, drawing upon early work by Rod Burstall.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The assertion language of separation logic is a special case of the logic of bunched implications (BI).
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A CACM review article by O'Hearn charts developments in the subject to early 2019.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Separation logic supports the developing field of research described by Peter O'Hearn and others as *local reasoning*, whereby specifications and proofs of a program component mention only the portion of memory used by the component, and not the entire global state of the system.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Applications include automated program verification (where an algorithm checks the validity of another algorithm) and automated parallelization of software.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Separation logic assertions describe "states" consisting of a *store* and a *heap*, roughly corresponding to the state of local (or *stack-allocated*) variables and *dynamically-allocated* objects in common programming languages such as C and Java.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A store s is a function mapping variables to values.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A heap h is a partial function mapping memory addresses to values.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Two heaps h and $h'$ are *disjoint* (denoted $h\,\bot \,h'$ ) if their domains do not overlap (i.e., for every memory address $\ell$ , at least one of $h(\ell )$ and $h'(\ell )$ is undefined).
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The logic allows to prove judgements of the form $s,h\models P$ , where s is a store, h is a heap, and P is an *assertion* over the given store and heap.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Separation logic assertions (denoted as P , Q , R ) contain the standard Boolean connectives and, in addition, $\mathbf {e} \mathbf {m} \mathbf {p}$ , $e\mapsto e'$ , $P\ast Q$ , and $P{-\!\!\ast }\,Q$ , where e and $e'$ are expressions.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The operators $\ast$ and $-\!\!\ast$ share some properties with the classical conjunction and implication operators.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] and they form an adjunction, i.e., $s,h\cup h'\models P\ast Q\Rightarrow R$ if and only if $s,h\models P\Rightarrow Q-\!\!\ast \,R$ for $h\,\bot \,h'$ ; more precisely, the adjoint operators are $\_\ast Q$ and $Q-\!\!\ast \,\_$ .
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] In separation logic, Hoare triples have a slightly different meaning than in Hoare logic.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The triple $\{P\}\ C\ \{Q\}$ asserts that if the program C executes from an initial state satisfying the precondition P then the program will *not go wrong* (e.g., have undefined behaviour), and if it terminates, then the final state will satisfy the postcondition Q .
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] In essence, during its execution, C may access only memory locations whose existence is asserted in the precondition or that have been allocated by C itself.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] This is known as the **frame rule** (named after the frame problem) and enables local reasoning.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] It says that a program that executes safely in a small state (satisfying P ), can also execute in any bigger state (satisfying $P\ast R$ ) and that its execution will not affect the additional part of the state (and so R will remain true in the postcondition).
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The side condition enforces this by specifying that none of the variables modified by C occur free in R , i.e. none of them are in the 'free variable' set ${\mathsf {fv}}$ of R .
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] More generally, separation logic can be seen as a way of reasoning about *separation algebras*.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A separation algebra may be defined in several ways, but is often presented as a cancellative, partial commutative monoid.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] It can be shown that the presentation of stacks and heaps above gives rise to a separation algebra: take *A* to be the set of all heaps, the binary operation $\oplus$ to be the union of two heaps (only defined when the heaps are disjoint), and *u* to be the empty heap.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] In some definitions, cancellativity is omitted, but this does not necessarily pose a problem.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The rules for $\land$ , $\vee$ , $\neg$ and $\exists$ are omitted but are easily derived from the above, while the semantics of $e\mapsto e'$ are given by the separation algebra in question.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Separation logic leads to simple proofs of pointer manipulation for data structures that exhibit regular sharing patterns which can be described simply using separating conjunctions; examples include singly and doubly linked lists and varieties of trees.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Graphs and DAGs and other data structures with more general sharing are more difficult for both formal and informal proof.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Separation logic has, nonetheless, been applied successfully to reasoning about programs with general sharing.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] In their POPL'01 paper, O'Hearn and Ishtiaq explained how the magic wand connective ${-\!\!*}$ could be used to reason in the presence of sharing, at least in principle.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] we obtain the weakest precondition for a statement that mutates the heap at location x , and this works for any postcondition, not only one that is laid out neatly using the separating conjunction.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] This idea was taken much further by Yang, who used ${-\!\!*}$ to provide localized reasoning about mutations in the classic Schorr-Waite graph marking algorithm.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Abstractly, $P\cup \!\!\!\!\!*Q$ can be seen to be a version of the fusion connective of relevance logic.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] which allows independent reasoning about threads that access separate storage.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] O'Hearn's proof rules adapted an early approach of Tony Hoare to reasoning about concurrency, replacing the use of scoping constraints to ensure separation by reasoning in separation logic.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Commenting on the early classical work on interference freedom by Susan Owicki and David Gries, O'Hearn says that explicit checking for non-interference isn't necessary because his system rules out interference in an implicit way, by the nature of the way proofs are constructed.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A model for concurrent separation logic was first provided by Stephen Brookes in a companion paper to O'Hearn's.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The soundness of the logic had been a difficult problem, and in fact a counterexample of John Reynolds had shown the unsoundness of an earlier, unpublished version of the logic; the issue raised by Reynolds's example is described briefly in O'Hearn's paper, and more thoroughly in Brookes's.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] At first it appeared that CSL was well suited to what Dijkstra had called loosely connected processes, but perhaps not to fine-grained concurrent algorithms with significant interference.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] However, gradually it was realized that the basic approach of CSL was considerably more powerful than first envisaged, if one employed non-standard models of the logical connectives and even the Hoare triples.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Finally, CSL-style principles have been used to compose reasoning about program histories instead of program states, in order to provide modular techniques for reasoning about fine-grained concurrent algorithms.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Versions of CSL have been included in many interactive and semi-automatic (or "in-between") verification tools as described in the next section.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] A particularly significant verification effort is that of the μC/OS-II kernel mentioned there.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] But, although steps have been made, as of yet CSL-style reasoning has been included in comparatively few tools in the automatic program analysis category (and none mentioned in the next section).
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] O'Hearn and Brookes are co-recipients of the 2016 Gödel Prize for their invention of Concurrent Separation Logic.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] This may be achieved by annotating each $\mapsto$ assertion with a fractional permission $\pi \in (0,1]$ as $e\,{\overset {\pi }{\mapsto }}\,e'$ .
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Note that the actual magnitudes of the permissions less than one are immaterial and only required for tracking purposes; a program should not concern itself over whether any given permission is 0.1 or 0.9, as it is able to read from the heap cell all the same.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] To allow for two heaps to both consider the same memory location, some modification is required to the definition of heaps and their disjointness.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The operation of merging two heaps will correspondingly add together permissions for those duplicated locations.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Tools for reasoning about programs fall on a spectrum from fully automatic program analysis tools, which do not require any user input, to interactive tools where the human is intimately involved in the proof process.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] Many such tools have been developed; the following list includes a few representatives in each category.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The distinction between interactive and in-between verifiers is not a sharp one.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] For example, Bedrock strives for a high degree of automation, in what it terms mostly-automatic verification, where Verifast sometimes requires annotations that resemble the tactics (little programs) used in interactive verifiers.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] The satisfiability problem for a quantifier-free, multi-sorted fragment of separation logic parameterized over the sorts of locations and data can be shown to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:separation-logic/concurrent-separation-logic] An algorithm for solving this fragment in DPLL(T)-based SMT solvers has been integrated into cvc5.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a **pointer** is an object in many programming languages that stores a memory address.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This can be that of another value located in computer memory, or in some cases, that of memory-mapped computer hardware.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer *references* a location in memory, and obtaining the value stored at that location is known as *dereferencing* the pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As an analogy, a page number in a book's index could be considered a pointer to the corresponding page; dereferencing such a pointer would be done by flipping to the page with the given page number and reading the text found on that page.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The actual format and content of a pointer variable is dependent on the underlying computer architecture.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Using pointers significantly improves performance for repetitive operations, like traversing iterable data structures (e.g. strings, lookup tables, control tables, linked lists, and tree structures).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In particular, it is often much cheaper in time and space to copy and dereference pointers than it is to copy and access the data to which the pointers point.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are also used to hold the addresses of entry points for called subroutines in procedural programming and for run-time linking to dynamic link libraries (DLLs).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In object-oriented programming, pointers to functions are used for binding methods, often using virtual method tables.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer is a simple, more concrete implementation of the more abstract *reference* data type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Several languages, especially low-level languages, support some type of pointer, although some have more restrictions on their use than others.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because pointers allow both protected and unprotected access to memory addresses, there are risks associated with using them, particularly in the latter case.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Primitive pointers are often stored in a format similar to an integer; however, attempting to dereference or "look up" such a pointer whose value is not a valid memory address could cause a program to crash (or contain invalid data).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To alleviate this potential problem, as a matter of type safety, pointers are considered a separate type parameterized by the type of data they point to, even if the underlying representation is an integer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other measures may also be taken (such as validation and bounds checking), to verify that the pointer variable contains a value that is both a valid memory address and within the numerical range that the processor is capable of addressing.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 1955, Soviet Ukrainian computer scientist Kateryna Yushchenko created the Address programming language that made possible indirect addressing and addresses of the highest rank – analogous to pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This language was widely used on the Soviet computers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, it was unknown outside the Soviet Union and usually Harold Lawson is credited with the invention, in 1964, of the pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 2000, Lawson was presented the Computer Pioneer Award by the IEEE "[f]or inventing the pointer variable and introducing this concept into PL/I, thus providing for the first time, the capability to flexibly treat linked lists in a general-purpose high-level language".
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] His seminal paper on the concepts appeared in the June 1967 issue of CACM entitled: PL/I List Processing.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the **word** *pointer* first appeared in print as a *stack pointer* in a technical memorandum by the System Development Corporation.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a pointer is a kind of reference.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data primitive* (or just *primitive*) is any datum that can be read from or written to computer memory using one memory access (for instance, both a *byte* and a *word* are primitives).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data aggregate* (or just *aggregate*) is a group of primitives that are logically contiguous in memory and that are viewed collectively as one datum (for instance, an aggregate could be 3 logically contiguous bytes, the values of which represent the 3 coordinates of a point in space).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When an aggregate is entirely composed of the same type of primitive, the aggregate may be called an *array*; in a sense, a multi-byte *word* primitive is an array of bytes, and some programs use words in this way.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the context of these definitions, a *byte* is the smallest primitive; each memory address specifies a different byte.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The memory address of the initial byte of a datum is considered the memory address (or *base memory address*) of the entire datum.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *memory pointer* (or just *pointer*) is a primitive, the value of which is intended to be used as a memory address; it is said that *a pointer points to a memory address*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It is also said that *a pointer points to a datum [in memory]* when the pointer's value is the datum's memory address.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] More generally, a pointer is a kind of reference, and it is said that *a pointer references a datum stored somewhere in memory*; to obtain that datum is *to dereference the pointer*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The feature that separates pointers from other kinds of reference is that a pointer's value is meant to be interpreted as a memory address, which is a rather low-level concept.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] References serve as a level of indirection: A pointer's value determines which memory address (that is, which datum) is to be used in a calculation.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because indirection is a fundamental aspect of algorithms, pointers are often expressed as a fundamental data type in programming languages; in statically (or strongly) typed programming languages, the type of a pointer determines the type of the datum to which the pointer points.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are a very thin abstraction on top of the addressing capabilities provided by most modern architectures.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The system would then also provide an operation to retrieve the value stored in the memory unit at a given address (usually utilizing the machine's general-purpose registers).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the usual case, a pointer is large enough to hold more addresses than there are units of memory in the system.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This introduces the possibility that a program may attempt to access an address which corresponds to no unit of memory, either because not enough memory is installed (i.e. beyond the range of available memory) or the architecture does not support such addresses.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The first case may, in certain platforms such as the Intel x86 architecture, be called a segmentation fault (segfault).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The second case is possible in the current implementation of AMD64, where pointers are 64 bit long and addresses only extend to 48 bits.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers must conform to certain rules (canonical addresses), so if a non-canonical pointer is dereferenced, the processor raises a general protection fault.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On the other hand, some systems have more units of memory than there are addresses.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this case, a more complex scheme such as memory segmentation or paging is employed to use different parts of the memory at different times.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last incarnations of the x86 architecture support up to 36 bits of physical memory addresses, which were mapped to the 32-bit linear address space through the PAE paging mechanism.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Thus, only 1/16 of the possible total memory may be accessed at a time.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In order to provide a consistent interface, some architectures provide memory-mapped I/O, which allows some addresses to refer to units of memory while others refer to device registers of other devices in the computer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] There are analogous concepts such as file offsets, array indices, and remote object references that serve some of the same purposes as addresses for other types of objects.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are directly supported without restrictions in languages such as PL/I, C, C++, Pascal, FreeBASIC, and implicitly in most assembly languages.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They are used mainly to construct references, which in turn are fundamental to construct nearly all data structures, and to pass data between different parts of a program.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In functional programming languages that rely heavily on lists, data references are managed abstractly by using primitive constructs like cons and the corresponding elements car and cdr, which can be thought of as specialised pointers to the first and second components of a cons-cell.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This gives rise to some of the idiomatic "flavour" of functional programming.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By structuring data in such cons-lists, these languages facilitate recursive means for building and processing data—for example, by recursively accessing the head and tail elements of lists of lists; e.g.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By contrast, memory management based on pointer dereferencing in some approximation of an array of memory addresses facilitates treating variables as slots into which data can be assigned imperatively.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When dealing with arrays, the critical lookup operation typically involves a stage called *address calculation* which involves constructing a pointer to the desired data element in the array.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In other data structures, such as linked lists, pointers are used as references to explicitly tie one piece of the structure to another.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to pass parameters by reference.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is useful if the programmer wants a function's modifications to a parameter to be visible to the function's caller.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is also useful for returning multiple values from a function.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can also be used to allocate and deallocate dynamic variables and arrays in memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Since a variable will often become redundant after it has served its purpose, it is a waste of memory to keep it, and therefore it is good practice to deallocate it (using the original pointer reference) when it is no longer needed.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Failure to do so may result in a *memory leak* (where available free memory gradually, or in severe cases rapidly, diminishes because of an accumulation of numerous redundant memory blocks).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This declares a variable `ptr` that stores a pointer to an object of type `int`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other types can be used in place of `int`; for example, `bool *ptr` would declare a pointer to an object of type `bool`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] After a pointer has been declared, it can be assigned an address.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Both `int *x, y;` and `int* x, y;` declare `x` to be a pointer to `int`, but declare `y` to be an `int`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is because the `*` applies only to the variable immediately following it.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The asterisk can also be used on the left-hand side of an assignment to change the object `a` without having to be in the same scope.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If `a` is accessed later, its new value will be 8.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because the C language does not specify an implicit initialization for objects of automatic storage duration, pointer variables can sometimes point to unexpected locations, causing undefined behavior.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To combat this, pointers are sometimes initialized with a null pointer value, represented in C by the `NULL` macro; in C23 and later, `nullptr` is also available as an alternative, which is of type `nullptr_t`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dereferencing a null pointer produces undefined behavior, which can result in unpredictable bugs and results.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This example may be clearer if memory is examined directly.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assume that `a` is located at address 0x8130 in memory and `ptr` at 0x8134; also assume this is a 32-bit machine such that an int is 32-bits wide.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Clearly, accessing `a` will yield the value of 8 because the previous instruction modified the contents of `a` by way of the pointer `ptr`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When setting up data structures like lists, queues and trees, it is necessary to have pointers to help manage how the structure is implemented and controlled.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Typical examples of pointers are start pointers, end pointers, and stack pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Relative addresses are a form of manual memory segmentation, and share many of its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A two-byte offset, containing a 16-bit, unsigned integer, can be used to provide relative addressing for up to 64 KiB (216 bytes) of a data structure.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Generally, though, such schemes are a lot of trouble, and for convenience to the programmer absolute addresses (and underlying that, a *flat address space*) is preferred.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A one byte offset, such as the hexadecimal ASCII value of a character (e.g.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] X'29') can be used to point to an alternative integer value (or index) in an array (e.g., X'01').
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this way, characters can be very efficiently translated from 'raw data' to a usable sequential index and then to an absolute address without a lookup table.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allocates a block of five integers and names the block `a`; the expression `a` evaluates, in most contexts, as a pointer to the first element of the block.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Another common use of pointers is to point to dynamically allocated memory from malloc which returns a consecutive block of memory of no less than the requested size that can be used as an array.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While, when used as an operand for most operators, an array evaluates as a pointer to the first element of the array, this is not the case for the `sizeof` operator.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this example, `sizeof(a)` will evaluate to `5 * sizeof(int)` (the size of the array), while `sizeof(ptr)` will evaluate to `sizeof(int *)`, the size of the pointer itself.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Represented here are five integers: 2, 4, 3, 1, and 5.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] These five integers occupy 32 bits (4 bytes) each with the least-significant byte stored first (this is a little-endian CPU architecture) and are stored consecutively starting at address 0x1000.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last example is how to access the contents of `a`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Below is an example definition of a linked list in C.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] where `Nil` is the empty list, and `Cons a (LinkedList a)` is a cons cell of type `a` with another link also of type `a`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The definition with references, however, is type-checked and does not use potentially confusing signal values.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this reason, data structures in C are usually dealt with via wrapper functions, which are carefully checked for correctness.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can be used to pass variables by their address, allowing their value to be changed.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some programs, the required amount of memory depends on what *the user* may enter.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In such cases the programmer needs to allocate memory dynamically.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is done by allocating memory at the *heap* rather than on the *stack*, where variables usually are stored (although variables can also be stored in the CPU registers).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dynamic memory allocation can only be made through pointers, and names – like with common variables – cannot be given.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to store and manage the addresses of dynamically allocated blocks of memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Such blocks are used to store data objects or arrays of objects.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Most structured and object-oriented languages provide an area of memory, called the *heap* or *free store*, from which objects are dynamically allocated.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The example C code below illustrates how structure objects are dynamically allocated and referenced.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `malloc()` for allocating memory blocks from the heap.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It takes the size of an object to allocate as a parameter and returns a pointer to a newly allocated block of memory suitable for storing the object, or it returns a null pointer if the allocation failed.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The code below illustrates how memory objects are dynamically deallocated, i.e., returned to the heap or free store.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `free()` for deallocating a previously allocated memory block and returning it back to the heap.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On some computing architectures, pointers can be used to directly manipulate memory or memory-mapped devices.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assigning addresses to pointers is an invaluable tool when programming microcontrollers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the mid-1980s, using the BIOS to access the video capabilities of PCs was slow.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Applications that were display-intensive typically used to access CGA video memory directly by casting the hexadecimal constant 0xB8000 to a pointer to an array of 80 unsigned 16-bit int values.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Each value consisted of an ASCII code in the low byte, and a colour in the high byte.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Control tables that are used to control program flow usually make extensive use of pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers, usually embedded in a table entry, may, for instance, be used to hold the entry points to subroutines to be executed, based on certain conditions defined in the same table entry.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers can however be simply indexes to other separate, but associated, tables comprising an array of the actual addresses or the addresses themselves (depending upon the programming language constructs available).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They can also be used to point to earlier table entries (as in loop processing) or forward to skip some table entries (as in a switch or "early" exit from a loop).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this latter purpose, the "pointer" may simply be the table entry number itself and can be transformed into an actual address by simple arithmetic.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In many languages, pointers have the additional restriction that the object they point to has a specific type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, a pointer may be declared to point to an integer; the language will then attempt to prevent the programmer from pointing it to objects which are not integers, such as floating-point numbers, eliminating some errors.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `money` would be an integer pointer and `bags` would be a char pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] because `money` and `bags` were declared with different types.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] which says to cast the integer pointer of `money` to a char pointer and assign to `bags`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A 2005 draft of the C standard requires that casting a pointer derived from one type to one of another type should maintain the alignment correctness for both types (6.3.2.3 Pointers, par.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that allow pointer arithmetic, arithmetic on pointers takes into account the size of the type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, adding an integer number to a pointer produces another pointer that points to an address that is higher by that number times the size of the type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allows us to easily compute the address of elements of an array of a given type, as was shown in the C arrays example above.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When a pointer of one type is cast to another type of a different size, the programmer should expect that pointer arithmetic will be calculated differently.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C, for example, if the `money` array starts at 0x2000 and `sizeof(int)` is 4 bytes whereas `sizeof(char)` is 1 byte, then `money + 1` will point to 0x2004, but `bags + 1` would point to 0x2001.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other risks of casting include loss of data when "wide" data is written to "narrow" locations (e.g.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `bags[0] = 65537;`), unexpected results when bit-shifting values, and comparison problems, especially with signed vs unsigned values.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Although it is impossible in general to determine at compile-time which casts are safe, some languages store run-time type information which can be used to confirm that these dangerous casts are valid at runtime.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other languages merely accept a conservative approximation of safe casts, or none at all.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C and C++, even if two pointers compare as equal that doesn't mean they are equivalent.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In these languages *and* LLVM, the rule is interpreted to mean that "just because two pointers point to the same address, does not mean they are equal in the sense that they can be used interchangeably", the difference between the pointers referred to as their *provenance*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Casting to an integer type such as `uintptr_t` is implementation-defined and the comparison it provides does not provide any more insight as to whether the two pointers are interchangeable.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In addition, further conversion to bytes and arithmetic will throw off optimizers trying to keep track the use of pointers, a problem still being elucidated in academic research.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As a pointer allows a program to attempt to access an object that may not be defined, pointers can be the origin of a variety of programming errors.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, the usefulness of pointers is so great that it can be difficult to perform programming tasks without them.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Consequently, many languages have created constructs designed to provide some of the useful features of pointers without some of their pitfalls, also sometimes referred to as *pointer hazards*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this context, pointers that directly address memory (as used in this article) are referred to as **raw pointers** or **naked pointer**, by contrast with smart pointers or other variants.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] One major problem with pointers is that as long as they can be directly manipulated as a number, they can be made to point to unused addresses or to data which is being used for other purposes.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Array indexing is handled as a special case.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer which does not have any address assigned to it is called a wild pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Any attempt to use such uninitialized pointers can cause unexpected behavior, either because the initial value is not a valid address, or because using it may damage other parts of the program.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The result is often a segmentation fault, storage violation or wild branch (if used as a function pointer or branch address).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In systems with explicit memory allocation, it is possible to create a dangling pointer by deallocating the memory region it points into.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This type of pointer is dangerous and subtle because a deallocated memory region may contain the same data as it did before it was deallocated but may be then reallocated and overwritten by unrelated code, unknown to the earlier code.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Languages with garbage collection prevent this type of error because deallocation is performed automatically when there are no more references in scope.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that abstract away pointers and pointer arithmetic, such as Java, one can use iterators, which can be seen as a safer means of iterating over a segment of memory or a collection without using direct pointer access.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Many languages, even those with pointers, such as C++, C# and Rust, have iterators for collections.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C++ the iterator can overload `operator++`, similar to the traditional syntax of incrementing a pointer in C.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Some languages, like C++, support smart pointers, which use a simple form of reference counting to help track allocation of dynamic memory in addition to acting as a reference.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the absence of reference cycles, where an object refers to itself indirectly through a sequence of smart pointers, these eliminate the possibility of dangling pointers and memory leaks.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Delphi strings support reference counting natively.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The Rust programming language introduces a *borrow checker*, *pointer lifetimes*, and an optimisation based around option types for null pointers to eliminate pointer bugs, without resorting to garbage collection.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **null pointer** has a value reserved for indicating that the pointer does not refer to a valid object.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Null pointers are routinely used to represent conditions such as the end of a list of unknown length or the failure to perform some action; this use of null pointers can be compared to nullable types and to the *Nothing* value in an option type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **dangling pointer** is a pointer that does not point to a valid object and consequently may make a program crash or behave oddly.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the Pascal or C programming languages, pointers that are not specifically initialized may point to unpredictable addresses in memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Here, `p2` may point to anywhere in memory, so performing the assignment `*p2 = 'b';` can corrupt an unknown area of memory or trigger a segmentation fault.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Where a pointer is used as the address of the entry point to a program or start of a function which doesn't return anything and is also either uninitialized or corrupted, if a call or jump is nevertheless made to this address, a "wild branch" is said to have occurred.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In other words, a wild branch is a function pointer that is wild (dangling).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The consequences are usually unpredictable and the error may present itself in several different ways depending upon whether or not the pointer is a "valid" address and whether or not there is (coincidentally) a valid instruction (opcode) at that address.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The detection of a wild branch can present one of the most difficult and frustrating debugging exercises since much of the evidence may already have been destroyed beforehand or by execution of one or more inappropriate instructions at the branch location.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If available, an instruction set simulator can usually not only detect a wild branch before it takes effect, but also provide a complete or partial trace of its history.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The cited patent also uses the term **self-relative pointer** to mean the same thing.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A **based pointer** is a pointer whose value is an offset from the value of another pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This can be used to store and load blocks of data, assigning the address of the beginning of the block to the base pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some languages, a pointer can reference another pointer, requiring multiple dereference operations to get to the original value.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While each level of indirection may add a performance cost, it is sometimes necessary in order to provide correct behavior for complex data structures.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This implementation uses a pointer to the first element in the list as a surrogate for the entire list.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If a new value is added to the beginning of the list, `head` has to be changed to point to the new element.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this case, if the value of `item` is less than that of `head`, the caller's `head` is properly updated to the address of the new item.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some languages, a pointer can reference executable code, i.e., it can point to a function, method, or procedure.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A function pointer will store the address of a function to be invoked.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While this facility can be used to call functions dynamically, it is often a favorite technique of virus and other malicious software writers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C++, one may use a lambda (anonymous function) in place of a function pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In doubly linked lists or tree structures, a back pointer held on an element 'points back' to the item referring to the current element.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p01] These are useful for navigation and manipulation, at the expense of greater memory use.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Ada is a strongly typed language where all pointers are typed and only safe type conversions are permitted.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] All pointers are by default initialized to `null`, and any attempt to access data through a `null` pointer causes an exception to be raised.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers in Ada are called *access types*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Ada 83 did not permit arithmetic on access types (although many compiler vendors provided for it as a non-standard feature), but Ada 95 supports “safe” arithmetic on access types via the package `System.Storage_Elements`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Several old versions of BASIC for the Windows platform had support for `STRPTR()` to return the address of a string, and for `VARPTR()` to return the address of a variable.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Visual Basic 5 also had support for `OBJPTR()` to return the address of an object interface, and for an ADDRESSOF operator to return the address of a function.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The types of all of these are integers, but their values are equivalent to those held by pointer types.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Newer dialects of BASIC, such as FreeBASIC or BlitzMax, have exhaustive pointer implementations, however.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In FreeBASIC, arithmetic on ANY pointers (equivalent to C's `void *`) are treated as though the ANY pointer was a byte width.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] ANY pointers cannot be dereferenced, as in C.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Also, casting between ANY and any other type's pointers will not generate any warnings.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C pointers are variables that store addresses and can be *null*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Each pointer has a type it points to, but one can freely cast between pointer types.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, it is not possible to cast between a function pointer and an object pointer.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A special pointer type called the "void pointer" allows pointing to any (non-function) object, but is limited by the fact that it cannot be dereferenced directly.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic provides the programmer with a single way of dealing with different types: adding and subtracting the number of elements required instead of the actual offset in bytes.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In particular, the C standard explicitly declares that the syntax `a[n]`, which is the n-th element of the array `a`, is equivalent to `*(a + n)`, which is the content of the element pointed by `a + n`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This implies that, for example, `a[3]` and `3[a]` both access the fourth element of the array `a`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] While powerful, pointer arithmetic can be a source of computer bugs.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It tends to confuse novice programmers, forcing them into different contexts: an expression can be an ordinary arithmetic one or a pointer arithmetic one, and sometimes it is easy to mistake one for the other.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In response to this, many modern high-level computer languages do not permit direct access to memory using addresses.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The **`void` pointer**, or **`void *`**, is supported in ANSI C as a generic pointer type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer to `void` can store the address of any object (not function), and, is implicitly converted to any other object pointer type on assignment, but it must be explicitly cast if dereferenced.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Before ANSI C, K&R used `char *` for the "type-agnostic pointer" purpose.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C++ fully supports C pointers and C typecasting.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It also supports a new group of typecasting operators to help catch some unintended dangerous casts at compile-time.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C++ also supports another form of reference, quite different from a pointer, called simply a *reference* or *reference type*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Since C++11, the C++ standard library also provides smart pointers, which can be used in some situations as a safer alternative to primitive C pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] `std::unique_ptr` replaces the previous smart pointer std::auto_ptr, which was deprecated in C++11 and removed in C++17.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In contrast to C, C++ does not allow the implicit conversion of `void*` to other pointer types, even in assignments.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This was a design decision to avoid careless and even unintended casts, though most compilers only output warnings, not errors, when encountering other casts.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C++, there is no `void&` (reference to void) to complement `void*` (pointer to void), because references behave like aliases to the variables they point to, and there can never be a variable whose type is `void`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C++ pointers to non-static members of a class can be defined.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] If a class `MyClass` has a member `T a` then `&MyClass::a` is a pointer to the member `a` of type `T MyClass::*`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This member can be an object or a function.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They can be used on the right-hand side of operators `.*` and `->*` to access the corresponding member.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The `()` and `[]` have a higher priority than `*`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In the C# programming language, pointers are supported by either marking blocks of code that include pointers with the `unsafe` keyword, or through the `System.Runtime.CompilerServices` namespace for pointer access.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The syntax is essentially the same as in C++, and the address pointed can be either managed or unmanaged memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, pointers to managed memory (any pointer to a managed object) must be declared using the `fixed` keyword, which prevents the garbage collector from moving the pointed object as part of memory management while the pointer is in scope, thus keeping the pointer address valid.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, an exception to this is from using the `IntPtr` structure, which is a memory managed equivalent to `int*`, and does not require the `unsafe` keyword nor the `CompilerServices` assembly.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Most such methods have the same security permission requirements as unmanaged code, since they can affect arbitrary places in memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C# allows stack-allocated arrays in safe code using `System.Span`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] C#, like C and C++, also has a `void*` (void pointer) type, but it is highly unrecommended.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike C and C++, right-aligned asterisks are not accepted by the compiler.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In C and C++, this would declare `a` as `int*` and `b` as `int`, but in C# this declares both variables as `int*`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The COBOL programming language supports pointers to variables.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Primitive or group (record) data objects declared within the `LINKAGE SECTION` of a program are inherently pointer-based, where the only memory allocated within the program is space for the address of the data item (typically a single memory word).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In program source code, these data items are used just like any other `WORKING-STORAGE` variable, but their contents are implicitly accessed indirectly through their `LINKAGE` pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Memory space for each pointed-to data object is typically allocated dynamically using external `CALL` statements or via embedded extended language constructs such as `EXEC CICS` or `EXEC SQL` statements.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Extended versions of COBOL also provide pointer variables declared with `USAGE` `IS` `POINTER` clauses.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The values of such pointer variables are established and modified using `SET` and `SET` `ADDRESS` statements.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some extended versions of COBOL also provide `PROCEDURE-POINTER` variables, which are capable of storing the addresses of executable code.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The PL/I language provides full support for pointers to all data types (including pointers to structures), recursion, multitasking, string handling, and extensive built-in functions.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] PL/I was quite a leap forward compared to the programming languages of its time.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] PL/I pointers are untyped, and therefore no casting is required for pointer dereferencing or assignment.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The declaration syntax for a pointer is `DECLARE xxx POINTER;`, which declares a pointer named "xxx".
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are used with `BASED` variables.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A based variable can be declared with a default locator (`DECLARE xxx BASED(ppp);` or without (`DECLARE xxx BASED;`), where xxx is a based variable, which may be an element variable, a structure, or an array, and ppp is the default pointer).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Such a variable can be address without an explicit pointer reference (`xxx=1;`, or may be addressed with an explicit reference to the default locator (ppp), or to any other pointer (`qqq->xxx=1;`).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic is not explicitly part of the PL/I standard, but the `UNSPEC` builtin function and pseudo-variable allow pointer arithmetic and many compilers allow expressions of the form `ptr = ptr±expression`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] IBM PL/I also has the builtin function `PTRADD` to perform the arithmetic.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointer arithmetic is always performed in bytes.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] IBM *Enterprise* PL/I compilers have a new form of typed pointer called a `HANDLE`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The D programming language is a derivative of C and C++ which fully supports C pointers and C typecasting.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It supports pointer arithmetic, and also has pointer slices.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer in D can decay to `void*` implicitly.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In D, it is possible to use `ref` for a reference, which automatically dereferences, disallows pointer arithmetic, and does not allow escaping a function (i.e. through `return`).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer slice can be seen as a pointer with a length.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Eiffel object-oriented language employs value and reference semantics without pointer arithmetic.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Nevertheless, pointer classes are provided.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They offer pointer arithmetic, typecasting, explicit memory management, interfacing with non-Eiffel software, and other features.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran-90 introduced a strongly typed pointer capability.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran pointers contain more than just a simple memory address.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They also encapsulate the lower and upper bounds of array dimensions, strides (for example, to support arbitrary array sections), and other metadata.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] An *association operator*, `=>` is used to associate a `POINTER` to a variable which has a `TARGET` attribute.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Fortran-90 `ALLOCATE` statement may also be used to associate a pointer to a block of memory.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Fortran-2003 adds support for procedure pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Also, as part of the *C Interoperability* feature, Fortran-2003 supports intrinsic functions for converting C-style pointers into Fortran pointers and back.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Go has pointers, declared similar to C/C++ pointers but with the asterisk first.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] For example, a pointer to `T` is written `*T`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike C, Go has garbage collection, and disallows pointer arithmetic.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Reference types, like in C++, do not exist.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some built-in types, like maps and channels, are boxed (i.e. internally they are pointers to mutable structures), and are initialized using the `make` function.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In an approach to unified syntax between pointers and non-pointers, the arrow (`->`) operator has been dropped: the dot operator on a pointer refers to the field or method of the dereferenced object.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This, however, only works with one level of indirection.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] There is no explicit representation of pointers in Java.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Instead, more complex data structures like objects and arrays are implemented using references.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The language does not provide any explicit pointer manipulation operators.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It is still possible for code to attempt to dereference a null reference (null pointer), however, which throws a java.lang.NullPointerException.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The space occupied by unreferenced memory objects is recovered automatically by garbage collection at run-time.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Java provides the classes `java.lang.ref.WeakReference` and `java.lang.ref.PhantomReference`, which respectively implement weak references and phantom references.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are implemented very much as in Pascal, as are `VAR` parameters in procedure calls.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Modula-2 is even more strongly typed than Pascal, with fewer ways to escape the type system.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Some of the variants of Modula-2 (such as Modula-3) include garbage collection.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Much as with Modula-2, pointers are available.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] There are still fewer ways to evade the type system and so Oberon and its variants are still safer with respect to pointers than Modula-2 or its variants.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] As with Modula-3, garbage collection is a part of the language specification.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Unlike many languages that feature pointers, standard ISO Pascal only allows pointers to reference dynamically created variables that are anonymous and does not allow them to reference standard static or local variables.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers also must have an associated type and a pointer to one type is not compatible with a pointer to another type (e.g. a pointer to a char is not compatible with a pointer to an integer).
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] This helps eliminate the type security issues inherent with other pointer implementations, particularly those used for PL/I or C.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It also removes some risks caused by dangling pointers, but the ability to dynamically let go of referenced space by using the `dispose` standard procedure (which has the same effect as the `free` library function found in C) means that the risk of dangling pointers has not been eliminated.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] However, in some commercial and open source Pascal (or derivatives) compiler implementations —like Free Pascal, Turbo Pascal or the Object Pascal in Embarcadero Delphi— a pointer is allowed to reference standard static or local variables and can be cast from one pointer type to another.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Moreover, pointer arithmetic is unrestricted: adding or subtracting from a pointer moves it by that number of bytes in either direction, but using the `Inc` or `Dec` standard procedures with it moves the pointer by the size of the data type it is *declared* to point to.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] An untyped pointer is also provided under the name `Pointer`, which is compatible with other pointer types.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Pointers are declared by use of the dereference operator `^`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] When it is used in the definition of a variable, the pointer is a reference to a type, which is either intrinsic (defined by the language compiler) or explicitly declared, either in another unit, in the current unit or the main program.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Line 2 shows the creation of a new type *months* and creates named constants of the months of the year.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Line 3 defines a pointer to a record type.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Lines 12-15 define the pointer variables; line 13 defines a pointer to a scalar and lines 14-15 create a linked list.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Line 18 allocates memory through the *new* function, and stores the address of that memory to the variable *calendar*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Line 26 shows assignment to the memory pointed to by the pointer *that*.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Lines 28 to 31 show the creation of a new link in the linked list.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Lines 33-35 release the memory allocated to those pointers.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] The Perl programming language supports pointers, although rarely used, in the form of the pack and unpack functions.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] These are intended only for simple interactions with compiled OS libraries.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In all other cases, Perl uses references, which are typed and do not allow any form of pointer arithmetic.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] They are used to construct complex data structures.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Rust uses references, which are similar to pointers but guaranteed to point to a valid value.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Working with raw pointers is less common, generally for low-level systems programming.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Raw pointers can only be dereferenced inside an `unsafe` block.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] Operations with raw pointers are found in `std::ptr`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] In Rust, there is no null pointer constant.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] It is instead given by `std::ptr::null()`.
[src:separation-logic/pointer-computer-programming-p02] A pointer to `T` is written as `*const T` or `*mut T` in Rust.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] In program analysis, **shape analysis** is a static code analysis technique that discovers and verifies properties of linked, dynamically allocated data structures in (usually imperative) computer programs.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] It is typically used at compile time to find software bugs or to verify high-level correctness properties of programs.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] In Java programs, it can be used to ensure that a sort method correctly sorts a list.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] For C programs, it might look for places where a block of memory is not properly freed.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Shape analysis is a form of pointer analysis, although it is more precise than typical pointer analysis.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Pointer analysis attempts to determine the set of objects to which a pointer can point (called the points-to set of the pointer).
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Unfortunately, these analysis are necessarily approximate (since a perfectly precise static analysis could solve the halting problem).
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Shape analysis can determine smaller (more precise) points-to sets.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Consider the following simple C++ program.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] This program builds an array of objects, processes them in some arbitrary way, and then deletes them.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Assuming that the `process_items` function is free of errors, it is clear that the program is safe: it never references freed memory, and it deletes all the objects that it has constructed.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Unfortunately, most pointer analyses have difficulty analyzing this program precisely.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] In order to determine points-to sets, a pointer analysis must be able to *name* a program's objects.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] In general, programs can allocate an unbounded number of objects; but in order to terminate, a pointer analysis can only use a finite set of names.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] A typical approximation is to give all the objects allocated on a given line of the program the same name.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] In the example above, all the objects constructed at line [1] would have the same name.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Therefore, when the `delete` statement is analyzed for the first time, the analysis determines that one of the objects named [1] is being deleted.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] The second time the statement is analyzed (since it is in a loop) the analysis warns of a possible error: since it is unable to distinguish the objects in the array, it may be that the second `delete` is deleting the same object as the first `delete`.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] This warning is spurious, and the goal of shape analysis is to avoid such warnings.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Shape analysis overcomes the problems of pointer analysis by using a more flexible naming system for objects.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Rather than giving an object the same name throughout a program, objects can change names depending on the program's actions.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Sometimes, several distinct objects with different names may be *summarized,* or merged, so that they have the same name.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Then, when a summarized object is about to be used by the program, it can be *materialized*—that is, the summarized object is split into two objects with distinct names, one representing a single object and the other representing the remaining summarized objects.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] The basic heuristic of shape analysis is that objects that are being used by the program are represented using unique materialized objects, while objects not in use are summarized.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] The array of objects in the example above is summarized in separate ways at lines [1], [2], and [3].
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] At line [1], the array has been only partly constructed.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] The array elements 0..i-1 contain constructed objects.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] The array element i is about to be constructed, and the following elements are uninitialized.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] After the loop terminates, at line [2], there is no need to keep anything materialized.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] At line [3], however, the array element `i` is in use again.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Therefore, the analysis splits the array into three segments as in line [1].
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] This time, though, the first segment before `i` has been deleted, and the remaining elements are still valid (assuming the `delete` statement hasn't executed yet).
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Notice that in this case, the analysis recognizes that the pointer at index `i` has not been deleted yet.
[src:separation-logic/shape-analysis-program-analysis] Therefore, it doesn't warn of a double deletion.
